I am pretty sure this is a typo, but you never know...Â  -dr palladino|Ok, so after chasing a fair amount of rabbit holes, I think that if this Mithradates was to be anyone found elsewhere in the historical record, it would Mithradates, Satrap of Cappadocia. The Greek in this section and later in 7.8.25, when the satrap is mentioned, is the same (ÎÎ¹Î¸ÏÎ±Î´Î¬ÏÎ·Ï). Mithradates of Cius, mentioned in Xenophon's Cyropaedia (who also might be the same person as Mithradates II of Cius(??) who is mentioned by Diodorus) has a one-letter difference (ÎÎ¹Î¸ÏÎ¹Î´Î¬ÏÎ·Ï). This is absolutely not strong evidence on its own, and I think it's entirely plausible the letter was changed when the name was Latinized (or it's a mispelling). However, if Mithradates of Cius and Mithradates II of Cius are the same person, than it's extremely unlikely he is this Mithradates, as Lucian of Samosata gives Mithradates II of Cius' age at death as 84 in what is now 302 BCE, which means he wouldn't have even been born by the time the Anabasis takes place, and Lucian would have to be off by ~30 years or so for it to line up.Â  Due to the lack of decisive evidence, however, I won't be linking Satrap Mithradates' wikipedia entry to this annotation and will leave it blank.

Case study because this may be the same person as Cleanor the Arcadian, but maybe not as he could be from Orchomenus, Boeotia instead|As of right now, immediately after looking at this passage for the first time, I'm leaning towards it could be Orchomenus, Boeotia because Xenophon 1) doesn't abbreviate this Cleanor to just "Cleanor" like he does with other people, signaling that there could be at least two important Cleanor's, and 2) It doesn't seem logical that Xenophon would refer to this same Cleanor entity by two different locations "of Arcadia" vs. "of Orchomenus" if this Orchomenus was in the region of Arcadia; in other words, Orchomnenus, Arcadia, doesn't seem to be noteworthy enough of a settlement to warrant it's own call out.
